## 6. Implementation Notes

### Deployment
Forgejo is deployed as a Docker container managed by Coolify on the Hetzner CX32 node. The `docker-compose.yml` for Forgejo is committed to the infrastructure repository and is the authoritative deployment definition.

```yaml
services:
  forgejo:
    image: codeberg.org/forgejo/forgejo:latest
    environment:
      - USER_UID=1000
      - USER_GID=1000
    volumes:
      - forgejo-data:/data
    ports:
      - "3000:3000"
      - "22:22"
    restart: unless-stopped
```

### Repository structure
All pipeline components follow a monorepo layout within Forgejo:

```
/
├── .forgejo/workflows/     # Forgejo Actions CI/CD definitions
├── docs/adr/               # Architecture Decision Records (this file)
├── tier-1-scout/           # Agent code per tier
├── tier-2-research/
├── tier-3-builder/
├── tier-4-qa/
├── tier-5-notifier/
├── tier-6-publisher/
├── windmill/               # Windmill workflow definitions
├── infrastructure/         # Docker Compose, Coolify config
└── prompts/                # Versioned prompt templates
```

### Webhook configuration
All Windmill trigger endpoints are registered as Forgejo webhooks with HMAC-SHA256 signature verification. Webhook payloads are validated in every Windmill script before processing:

```python
import hmac, hashlib

def verify_forgejo_webhook(payload: bytes, signature: str, secret: str) -> bool:
    expected = hmac.new(secret.encode(), payload, hashlib.sha256).hexdigest()
    return hmac.compare_digest(f"sha256={expected}", signature)
```

### Backup
Forgejo data volume is included in the Hetzner automated snapshot schedule. A secondary backup script commits a Forgejo dump to an off-site S3-compatible bucket (Hetzner Object Storage) on a daily cron via Forgejo Actions.

